   <h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Corruption Perceptions Index</h1> 
   <div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content"> 
    <div id="siteSub" class="noprint">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div> 
    <div id="contentSub"></div> 
    <div id="contentSub2"></div> 
    <div id="jump-to-nav"></div> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">Jump to search</a>

        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The <b>Corruption Perceptions Index</b> (<b>CPI</b>) is an index <a href="/wiki/Published" class="mw-redirect" title="Published">published</a> annually by Berlin-based <a href="/wiki/Transparency_International" title="Transparency International">Transparency International</a> since 1995 which ranks countries "by their perceived levels of <a href="/wiki/Public_sector" title="Public sector">public sector</a><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> corruption, as determined by expert assessments and opinion surveys."<sup id="cite_ref-cpi_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpi-2">[2]</a></sup> The CPI generally defines <a href="/wiki/Corruption" title="Corruption">corruption</a> as "the misuse of public power for private benefit".<sup id="cite_ref-cpilong2_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpilong2-3">[3]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The 2019 CPI, published in January of 2020, currently ranks 180 countries "on a scale from 100 (very clean) to 0 (highly corrupt)."<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> In the list, <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a>, <a href="/wiki/Finland" title="Finland">Finland</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">New Zealand</a>, <a href="/wiki/Sweden" title="Sweden">Sweden</a>, <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a> and <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a> are perceived as the top 6 least corrupt nations in the world, ranking consistently high among international <a href="/wiki/Financial_transparency" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial transparency">financial transparency</a>, while the most perceived corrupt country in the world is <a href="/wiki/Somalia" title="Somalia">Somalia</a>, scoring 8–10 out of 100 since 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-cpidetail_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpidetail-5">[5]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/South_Sudan" title="South Sudan">South Sudan</a> is also perceived as one of the most corrupt countries in the world due to constant social and economic crises, ranking an average score of 13 out of 100 in 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading">

        </tr>
        <tr>
         <td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r992953826">.mw-parser-output .navbar{display:inline;font-size:88%;font-weight:normal}.mw-parser-output .navbar-collapse{float:left;text-align:left}.mw-parser-output .navbar-boxtext{word-spacing:0}.mw-parser-output .navbar ul{display:inline-block;white-space:nowrap;line-height:inherit}.mw-parser-output .navbar-brackets::before{margin-right:-0.125em;content:"[ "}.mw-parser-output .navbar-brackets::after{margin-left:-0.125em;content:" ]"}.mw-parser-output .navbar li{word-spacing:-0.125em}.mw-parser-output .navbar-mini abbr{font-variant:small-caps;border-bottom:none;text-decoration:none;cursor:inherit}.mw-parser-output .navbar-ct-full{font-size:114%;margin:0 7em}.mw-parser-output .navbar-ct-mini{font-size:114%;margin:0 4em}.mw-parser-output .infobox .navbar{font-size:100%}.mw-parser-output .navbox .navbar{display:block;font-size:100%}.mw-parser-output .navbox-title .navbar{float:left;text-align:left;margin-right:0.5em}</style>
          <div class="navbar plainlinks hlist navbar-mini">
           <ul>
            <li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Political_corruption_sidebar" title="Template:Political corruption sidebar"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li>
            <li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Political_corruption_sidebar" title="Template talk:Political corruption sidebar"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li>
            <li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Political_corruption_sidebar&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li>
           </ul>
          </div></td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table> 
      <p><a href="/wiki/Transparency_International" title="Transparency International">Transparency International</a> commissioned the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Passau" title="University of Passau">University of Passau</a>'s <a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Graf_Lambsdorff" class="extiw" title="de:Johann Graf Lambsdorff">Johann Graf Lambsdorff</a> to produce the CPI.<sup id="cite_ref-2005FAQ_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2005FAQ-7">[7]</a></sup> The 2012 CPI takes into account 16 different surveys and assessments from 12 different institutions.<sup id="cite_ref-cpilong1_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpilong1-8">[8]</a></sup> The 13 surveys/assessments are either business people opinion surveys or performance assessments from a group of analysts.<sup id="cite_ref-cpilong2_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpilong2-3">[3]</a></sup> Early CPIs used public opinion surveys.<sup id="cite_ref-cpilong7_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpilong7-9">[9]</a></sup> The institutions are: </p> 
      <ul>
       <li><a href="/wiki/African_Development_Bank" title="African Development Bank">African Development Bank</a> (based in Ivory Coast)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Bertelsmann_Foundation" class="mw-redirect" title="Bertelsmann Foundation">Bertelsmann Foundation</a> (based in Germany)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Economist_Intelligence_Unit" title="Economist Intelligence Unit">Economist Intelligence Unit</a> (based in the UK)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Freedom_House" title="Freedom House">Freedom House</a> (based in the US)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Global_Insight" title="Global Insight">Global Insight</a> (based in US)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/International_Institute_for_Management_Development" title="International Institute for Management Development">International Institute for Management Development</a> (based in Switzerland)</li> 
       <li>Political and Economic Risk Consultancy (based in Hong Kong)</li> 
       <li>The PRS Group, Inc., (based in the US)</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/World_Economic_Forum" title="World Economic Forum">World Economic Forum</a></li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/World_Bank" title="World Bank">World Bank</a></li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/World_Justice_Project" title="World Justice Project">World Justice Project</a> (based in US)<sup id="cite_ref-cpisources_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpisources-10">[10]</a></sup></li>
      </ul> 
      <p>Countries need to be evaluated by at least three sources to appear in the CPI.<sup id="cite_ref-cpilong7_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpilong7-9">[9]</a></sup> The CPI measures perception of corruption due to the difficulty of measuring absolute levels of corruption.<sup id="cite_ref-cpifaq_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpifaq-11">[11]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Validity">Validity</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Corruption_Perceptions_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Validity">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>A study published in 2012 found a "very strong significant correlation" between the Corruption Perceptions Index and two other proxies for corruption: black market activity and an overabundance of regulation.<sup id="cite_ref-ivcp_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ivcp-12">[12]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>All three metrics also had a highly significant correlation with real gross domestic product per capita (RGDP/Cap); the Corruption Perceptions Index correlation with RGDP/Cap was the strongest, explaining over three fourths of the variance.<sup id="cite_ref-ivcp_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ivcp-12">[12]</a></sup> (Note that a lower on this scale reflects greater corruption, so that countries with higher RGDPs generally had less corruption.) </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Economic_implications">Economic implications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Corruption_Perceptions_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Economic implications">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>Research papers published in 2007 and 2008 examined the economic consequences of corruption perception, as defined by the CPI. The researchers found a correlation between a higher CPI and higher long-term economic growth,<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> as well as an increase in <a href="/wiki/GDP" class="mw-redirect" title="GDP">GDP</a> growth of 1.7% for every unit increase in a country's CPI score.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> Also shown was a <a href="/wiki/Power-law" class="mw-redirect" title="Power-law">power-law</a> dependence linking higher CPI score to higher rates of foreign investment in a country. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Rankings">Rankings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Corruption_Perceptions_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Rankings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>Legend: </p> 
      <table class="wikitable"> 
       <tbody>
        <tr> 
         <th rowspan="2">Scores </th>

        </tr>

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Criticism_and_limitations">Criticism and limitations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Corruption_Perceptions_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Criticism and limitations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>The Index has been criticized on the basis of its <a href="/wiki/Methodology" title="Methodology">methodology</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>According to political scientist Dan Hough, three flaws in the Index include:<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> </p> 
      <ul>
       <li>Corruption is too complex a concept to be captured by a single score. For instance, the nature of corruption in rural Kansas will be different from that in the city administration of New York, yet the Index measures them in the same way.</li> 
       <li>By measuring perceptions of corruption, as opposed to corruption itself, the Index may simply be reinforcing existing stereotypes and cliches.</li> 
       <li>The Index only measures public sector corruption, ignoring the private sector. This, for instance, means the well-publicized <a href="/wiki/Libor_scandal" title="Libor scandal">Libor scandal</a> or the <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen_emissions_scandal" title="Volkswagen emissions scandal">VW emissions scandal</a> are not counted as corrupt actions.</li>
      </ul> 
      <p>Media outlets frequently use the raw numbers as a yardstick for government performance, without clarifying what the numbers mean. The local Transparency International chapter in <a href="/wiki/Bangladesh" title="Bangladesh">Bangladesh</a> disowned the index results after a change in methodology caused the country's scores to increase; media reported it as an "improvement".<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In a 2013 article in <i><a href="/wiki/Foreign_Policy_(magazine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Foreign Policy (magazine)">Foreign Policy</a></i>, Alex Cobham suggested that CPI should be dropped for the good of Transparency International. It argues that the CPI embeds a powerful and misleading elite bias in popular perceptions of corruption, potentially contributing to a vicious cycle and at the same time incentivizing inappropriate policy responses. Cobham writes, "the index corrupts perceptions to the extent that it's hard to see a justification for its continuing publication."<sup id="cite_ref-Cobham,_Alex_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cobham,_Alex-30">[30]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>However, recent econometric analyses that have exploited the existence of natural experiments on the level of corruption and compared the CPI with other subjective indicators have found that, while not perfect, the CPI is argued to be broadly consistent with one-dimensional measures of corruption.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In the United States, many lawyers advise international businesses to consult the CPI when attempting to measure the risk of <a href="/wiki/Foreign_Corrupt_Practices_Act" title="Foreign Corrupt Practices Act">Foreign Corrupt Practices Act</a> violations in different nations. This practice has been criticized by the <i>Minnesota Journal of International Law</i>, which wrote that since the CPI may be subject to perceptual biases it therefore should not be considered by lawyers to be a measure of actual national corruption risk.<sup id="cite_ref-ssrn.com_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ssrn.com-32">[32]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Transparency International also publishes the <a href="/wiki/Global_Corruption_Barometer" title="Global Corruption Barometer">Global Corruption Barometer</a>, which ranks countries by corruption levels using direct surveys instead of perceived expert opinions, which has been under criticism for substantial bias from the powerful elite.<sup id="cite_ref-Cobham,_Alex_30-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cobham,_Alex-30">[30]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Transparency International has warned that a country with a clean CPI score may still be linked to corruption internationally. For example, while Sweden had the 3rd best CPI score in 2015, one of its state-owned companies, <a href="/wiki/TeliaSonera" class="mw-redirect" title="TeliaSonera">TeliaSonera</a>, was facing allegations of bribery in Uzbekistan.<sup id="cite_ref-cpi2015_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cpi2015-33">[33]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Corruption_Perceptions_Index&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

      </ul>

          <th scope="row" class="navbox-group" style="width:1%">Forms or aspects<br>of corruption</th>
          <td class="navbox-list navbox-odd hlist" style="text-align:left;border-left-width:2px;border-left-style:solid;width:100%;padding:0px">
           <div style="padding:0em 0.25em"></div>
           <table class="nowraplinks navbox-subgroup" style="border-spacing:0">
            <tbody>
             <tr>
              <th scope="row" class="navbox-group" style="width:1%">General</th>
              <td class="navbox-list navbox-odd" style="text-align:left;border-left-width:2px;border-left-style:solid;width:100%;padding:0px">
               <div style="padding:0em 0.25em"> 
                <ul>
                 <li><a href="/wiki/Baksheesh" title="Baksheesh">Baksheesh</a></li> 
                 <li><a href="/wiki/Black_market" title="Black market">Black market</a></li> 
                 <li><a href="/wiki/Bribery" title="Bribery">Bribery</a></li>
